unisi messaggio inoltrato oggetto seminario fisica sperimentale data fri may +0200 mittente carmen marinelli xxxxx xxx xxxxx xxx *mercoledì giugno 2019***** **ore aula 5**fisica** ****dsfta università siena *dr. luca marmugi* department of physics and astronomy university college london gower street london wc1e 6bt united kingdom /terrà seminario titolo biomedical imaging with atomic magnetometers progress and perspectives abstract building on recent demonstrations electromagnetic induction imaging with atomic magnetometers has paved the path to novel approach to biomedical imaging with the promise of non-invasive and safe /in vivo /mapping of organs and tissues dielectric properties this technique is expected to have tremendous impact research and clinical practice when electric conductivity plays or is predicted to play relevant role today this field actively investigated by various groups worldwide is at the edge of major breakthrough the requirements for imaging biological tissues are met and the first biomedical images appear to be close to realisation this talk the most recent progress imaging with atomic magnetometers will be reviewed the enabling features for biomedical imaging will be treated detail sensitivity of the atomic magnetometers extension to low-conductivity range phase and imaging stability sensitivity to spatial features and resolution operational configurations as well as perspectives for full 3d mapping and image reconstruction will be discussed c. deans l. marmugi s. hussain f. renzoni /electromagnetic induction imaging with radio-frequency atomic magnetometer https //aip.scitation.org/doi/10.1063/1.4943659 appl phys lett *108* l. marmugi f. renzoni /optical magnetic induction tomography of the heart https //www.nature.com/articles/srep23962 sci rep *6* l. marmugi c. deans f. renzoni /atomic magnetometry-based electromagnetic imaging of low-conductivity semiconductors https //arxiv.org/abs/1805.05743 arxiv:1805.05743 c. deans l. marmugi f. renzoni /sub-picotesla widely tunable atomic magnetometer operating at room-temperature unshielded environments https //arxiv.org/abs/1804.05124 rev sci instr *89* p. bevington r. gartman w. chalupczak c. deans l. marmugi f. renzoni /non-destructive structural imaging of steelwork with atomic magnetometers https //arxiv.org/abs/1808.03226 appl phys lett *113* y. cohen k. jadeja s. sula m. venturelli c. deans l. marmugi f. renzoni /a cold atom radio-frequency magnetometer https //arxiv.org/abs/1902.08258 appl phys lett *114* c. deans l. marmugi f. renzoni /active underwater detection with an array of atomic magnetometers https //www.osapublishing.org/ao/abstract.cfm uri=ao-57-10-2346 appl opt *57* c. deans l. d. griffin l. marmugi f. renzoni /machine learning based localization and classification with atomic magnetometers https //arxiv.org/abs/1710.06629 phys rev lett *120* interessati invitati partecipare https
